══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
I. PRIMARY LITERATURE: HETEROGENEOUS LLM STIGMERGY
══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

Traditional multi-agent LLM systems (e.g., AutoGen, ChatDev) rely on direct
message passing (Manager → Coder → Reviewer). This scales poorly, hallucinates,
and explodes API costs due to redundant context windows.

Recent research on Stigmergic LLM Coordination (2023-2025) proves a different path:
1. Indirect Interaction: Agents never talk to each other. They read/write to a
   shared "blackboard" or environment (in our case, the SIFTA filesystem and .jsonl ledgers).
2. Heterogeneity: Different models (Claude, Gemini, O3) have different cognitive
   profiles. Stigmergy allows them to contribute based on local pressure gradients
   without needing a central planner to assign tasks.
3. Emergence: System goals are achieved via accumulation of local modifications
   (e.g., AG31 fixing the math, C47H doing the architecture, C55M brute-forcing
   the terminal).

